               <persName><roleName type="title"> ʾalaqā, dabtarā, Ṣaḥāfe tǝʿǝzāz</roleName></persName>
                  <nationality type="Ethiopia"/>
                  <faith type="EOTC"/>
                  <occupation type="ecclesiastic"> chronicler </occupation>
               <birth when="1825">He was born at <placeName ref="LOC6381Yefat">Yǝfāt</placeName></birth>
               <floruit notBefore="1855" notAfter="1876"> He was the secretary of <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName><persName ref="PRS9430Tewodros">Tewodros II</persName>, a missionary and writer. 
                  He was converted to protestanism in <date>1858</date> by the influence of the missionaries, without officially leaving, 
                  however, the Ethiopian Orthodox Church . He was also a tutor of the son of  <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName><persName ref="PRS9430Tewodros">
                     Tewodros II</persName>, <roleName type="title">daǧǧāzmāč</roleName>
                  <persName ref="PRS1625Alamayy">ʾAlamāyyahu Tewodros</persName>.  
                  He was succeeded by <roleName type="title"> ʾalaqā </roleName><persName ref="PRS3808engedaW">ʾƎngǝdā Warq</persName> as a chief scribe. 
